     1	The Concept of Community Computing
     2	
     3	     Since 1985, Case Western Reserve University has been experimenting
     4	with free, open-access, community computer systems as a new communications
     5	and information medium. 
     6	
     7	     In effect, these systems represent a new application in computing. A 
     8	multi-user computer is established at a central location in a given area 
     9	and the machine is connected to the telephone system through a series of 
    10	devices called modems. Running on the machine is a computer program 
    11	that provides its users with everything from electronic mail services to 
    12	information about health care, education, technology, government, 
    13	recreation, or just about anything else the host operators would like to 
    14	place on the machine.
    15	
    16	     Anyone in the community with access to a home, office, or school 
    17	computer and a modem can contact the system any time, 24 hours a day. 
    18	They simply dial a central phone number, make connection, and a series of 
    19	menus appears on the screen which allows them to select the information 
    20	or communication services they would like. All of it is free and all of it 
    21	can easily be accomplished by a first-time user.
    22	
    23	     The key to the economics of operating a community computer system is 
    24	the fact that the system is literally run by the community itself. 
    25	Everything that appears on one of these machines is there because there 
    26	are individuals or organizations in the community who are prepared to 
    27	contribute their time, effort, and expertise to place it there and operate it 
    28	over time. This, of course, is in contrast to the commercial services 
    29	which have very high personnel and information-acquisition costs and 
    30	must pass those costs on to the consumer.
    31	
    32	     Couple this volunteerism with the rapidly-dropping costs of computing 
    33	power, the use of inexpensive transmission technology, and the fact that 
    34	the necessary software to operate these systems is available for low
    35	cost--and public access computing becomes an economically-viable entity.
    36	
    37	Case Reserve's Involvement in Community Computing
    38	
    39	     The University's involvement in the development of community 
    40	computer systems has its origins in an experiment conducted in the School 
    41	of Medicine in the fall of 1984. Dr. Tom Grundner of the Department of 
    42	Family Medicine, set up a single phone line, computerized, "Bulletin Board" 
    43	system called "St. Silicon's Hospital and Information Dispensary" to test 
    44	the efficacy of using this medium as a means of delivering general health 
    45	information to the public. The heart of the system was an interactive area 
    46	where lay people could call in using their home, school, or business 
    47	computers, leave medically-related questions, and have them answered by 
    48	a physician within 24 hours. The experiment proved so successful that it 
    49	attracted the attention of the Information Systems Division of AT&T and 
    50	the Ohio Bell Telephone Company, who supported a larger project to expand 
    51	and develop this interactive concept.
    52	
    53	     Based on these donations, Dr. Grundner began work on a full-scale 
    54	"community computer system" on an AT&T 3B2/400 computer with 10 
    55	incoming phone lines. This pilot project was designed to serve as a 
    56	community information resource in areas as diverse as law, medicine, 
    57	education, arts, sciences, and government--including free electronic mail 
    58	services for the citizens of northeast Ohio. On July 16, 1986, this system, 
    59	called the Cleveland Free-Net was opened by Ohio Governor Richard 
    60	Celeste and Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich and the project was 
    61	officially underway.
    62	
    63	     During its prototype stage, the Cleveland Free-Net gathered over 7000 
    64	registered users from throughout the Cleveland metropolitan area and 
    65	handled between 500-600 calls per day on 10 incoming phone lines. In 
    66	1989, however, it moved out of prototype in a big way.
    67	
    68	     A new system was designed around six IBM-RT (Model 135) computers 
    69	which would be linked together so that, from the user's standpoint, they 
    70	would appear as one big machine. This new system would provide the 
    71	Cleveland Free-Net  with 96 megabytes of RAM (96 million characters of 
    72	Random Access Memory), 2.3 gigabytes of hard disk storage (2.3 billion 
    73	characters of hard disk), and would be capable of supporting up to 360 
    74	simultaneous users.
    75	
    76	     In August of 1989 the Cleveland supersystem opened with 32 phone 
    77	lines on its way to a projected 96 lines by the end of the year. In August 
    78	also, the Free-Net was connected to the CWRUNET fiber-optic campus 
    79	network. This merger of a community computer system with a campus 
    80	network is yet another first and provides an entirely new model for 
    81	campus network development.
    82	
    83	     By the end of 1992 the Cleveland Free-Net had grown to over 36,000
    84	active accounts handling over 11,000 logins a day.
    85	
    86	Development of the Concept
    87	
    88	     As a result of the experience we have gained in working with and 
    89	developing these systems, several conclusions regarding community 
    90	computing can be drawn.
    91	
    92	     First, it is clear that these community computers represent the leading 
    93	edge of what can only be described as a new telecommunications medium. 
    94	Telecomputing is not radio, not television, not print, but has 
    95	characteristics of all three plus some additional ones of its own. This 
    96	fact alone will inevitably lead to developments and uses that we cannot 
    97	now even begin to imagine.
    98	
    99	     Second, experience in northeast Ohio indicates that a critical mass of 
   100	people now exist who are prepared to utilize this new medium. As more 
   101	and more modem-equipped microcomputers penetrate the home and 
   102	especially the work environment, the utility of public-access 
   103	computerized information services goes up. We have no doubt that this 
   104	consumer interest and ability to utilize this technology exists at least as 
   105	much in other parts of the country as it does in northeast Ohio.
   106	
   107	    Third, there is a certain sense of inevitability to the development of 
   108	community computing. Simply stated, given the directions now being taken 
   109	by the computer and communications industry, we find ourselves unable to 
   110	imagine a 21st century in which we do NOT have community computer 
   111	systems, just as this century has its public libraries. Moreover, we 
   112	believe that the community computer, as a resource, will have at least as 
   113	much impact on the next century as the public library has had on ours.
   114	
   115	     There currently exists an entire generation in our secondary schools 
   116	and colleges, for example, that have come to know the microcomputer as a 
   117	routine personal productivity tool. By the turn of the century, these people 
   118	will be in a work place where microcomputers and computerized 
   119	information retrieval will be ubiquitous. This, in turn, cannot help but lead 
   120	to a demand for similar functions in the home, even as the telephone 
   121	migrated from being primarily a business tool to a home utility. The 
   122	process, in effect, feeds on itself. Indeed, several sources are predicting 
   123	that by the year 2000, over 32,000,000 households (40% of all households) 
   124	will have some kind of in-home computing technology or information 
   125	service.
   126	
   127	     But perhaps the best way to illustrate the development of community 
   128	computing is by analogy to the development of the public library system in 
   129	our country. In the middle of the last century there was no such thing as 
   130	the free public library. Eventually the literacy rate increased enough (and 
   131	the cost of books decreased enough) that the public library became 
   132	feasible. In this century, we believe we have reached the point where 
   133	computer "literacy" has increased enough (and the cost of equipment 
   134	decreased enough) that a similar demand has formed for free, public-
   135	access, community computer systems. 
   136	
   137	A Civic Utility: Potential Impact on the Community
   138	
   139	     Who, exactly, benefits from community computing? To cite just a few 
   140	examples:
   141	
   142	     % The Citizens: First and foremost, these community computer systems 
   143	open up information services to very large populations that would 
   144	otherwise not be able to afford it. The cost of utilizing a Free-Net 
   145	community computer consists of the cost of having standard telephone 
   146	service in the home or business, plus the price of the equipment needed to 
   147	get online. This equipment is now well under $200 virtually anywhere, and 
   148	that is assuming the person purchases new. If a person wishes to attend a 
   149	few garage sales, flea markets, or computer fairs, it could be 
   150	considerably less.
   151	
   152	     % Public and Private Schools: Via community computers, school 
   153	systems finally have a cost-effective way to teach telecomputing to their 
   154	students, thereby sending a new generation of information-literate 
   155	citizens into the work force. In addition, these systems allow students, 
   156	teachers, parents, and administrators to communicate with each other and 
   157	have access to information bases of interest and importance.
   158	                                                                     
   159	     % Government: Community computers provide citizens with an 
   160	inexpensive and rapid way to make contact with their elected 
   161	representatives at the city, county, state, and national levels--contacts 
   162	which include everything from obtaining information on governmental 
   163	services to providing access to tax-payer supported, governmentally-
   164	produced databases. It should also be pointed out that these 
   165	communications are not one way. Elected representatives and other 
   166	officials also have the ability to electronically communicate with their 
   167	constituents.
   168	
   169	     % Small- and Medium-sized Businesses: Most major corporations have 
   170	electronic mail and other computer-driven information services at their 
   171	disposal. Most small- and medium-sized businesses do not. With a Free-
   172	Net system in place, these smaller enterprises are finally able to afford 
   173	to link their operations together via the free electronic mail services 
   174	found on these systems and have access to a variety of useful business 
   175	databases--something that cannot help but improve the business 
   176	infrastructure of any city.
   177	
   178	     % The Agricultural Community: Among the segments in our society that 
   179	were the first to embrace computing were our farmers. The reason was 
   180	obvious. Farmers are business people too, but they have the disadvantages 
   181	of, in general, being dispersed over wide geographic areas. A Free-Net 
   182	system in a central location in a county allows the agricultural 
   183	community to access common information bases, share solutions to farm-
   184	related problems, access up-to-date crop and price information, and make 
   185	electronic connection with the County Agent and each other--all without 
   186	ever leaving home.
   187	
   188	     % The Telecommunications and Videotex Industry: For years the 
   189	commercial videotex industry has been dividing, sub-dividing, and sub-sub-
   190	dividing essentially the same "up-scale" demographic group: $50,000+ 
   191	yearly household incomes, very well educated, overwhelmingly white, and 
   192	overwhelmingly male. If the industry is to survive and flourish, however, 
   193	it is going to have to find a way to penetrate the middle class with its 
   194	services. Free-Net community computers do exactly that. On the Cleveland 
   195	system, for example, we draw as many users out of the demographically 
   196	blue collar areas of the city as we do out of the wealthier sections. 
   197	Demographic penetration such as this, on a nationwide basis, is vital if 
   198	the telecomputing and videotex industry is to survive into the 21st 
   199	century. It is also important to the telephone industry, which has spent 
   200	millions of dollars on "intelligent gateway" technology, that videotex 
   201	flourish and that their services be used.
   202	
   203	     % Community Organizations and Institutions: Each Free-Net is set up 
   204	using an "Electronic City" motif. That motif was not selected by accident. 
   205	To one degree or another, virtually every institution in society has an 
   206	information dissemination function of some kind--a need to tell others 
   207	about itself and share its knowledge. The Free-Net makes it possible for 
   208	any and all of them to utilize a new medium to accomplish that goal. From 
   209	artistic and cultural organizations to medical institutions to hobbyists of 
   210	all kinds, all can find a place on a community computer.
